<HEAD>                          
<TITLE>NewsCAP</TITLE>                    
</HEAD>                       
<BODY BGCOLOR ="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#F50A2B" VLINK="#1F8F5F"        
ALINK="#FFFFFF">                   
<CENTER><FONT COLOR=#004080><H2>Virtual University NewsCAP</H2>                    
<H4><I>Newsletter of the Consortium for Academic Partnership</I></H4></FONT>                                     
<P>                                    
<P>      
<P>       
                     
Consortium for Academic Partnership<BR>             
888 Seventh Avenue, 31st Floor<BR>                
New York, NY 10106<BR>                     
Tel: (212) 887-0175 Fax: (212) 974-0367<BR>                        
E-mail: LStrashko@sorosny.org</CENTER>              
<P>           
<P>          
<P>                
<P>                
<IMG ALIGN=left SRC=point.jpg HEIGHT=77%>                         
<B>Martha Loerke, </B> Director <BR>            
<B>Carol Tegen, </B> Deputy Director<BR>          
<B>Amy Kehoe, </B>  Senior Program Officer<BR>             
<B>Vera Djomparin, </B> Senior Administrator<BR>                   
<B>Kristin Crosby, </B> Program Coordinator<BR>               
<B>Jennifer Kelleher, </B> Program Coordinator<BR>                
<B>Thouraya Raiss, </B> Program Coordinator<BR>            
<B>Larissa Strashko, </B> Program Assistant         
<P>                                                   
<B>CAP</B>, the scholarship arm of the Open Society Institute, funds students and                       
scholars from Central and Eastern Europe, the Newly Independent and Baltic          
States, and Burma to participate in a variety of rigorous and competitive     
academic exchange programs. Grants are awarded through open, merit-based        
competitions for study primarily in the humanities and social sciences.  The goals             
of the Consortium are to create lasting cross-national ties through the exploration of    
current political, economic, and social issues, and to provide grantees with the     
knowledge needed to foster open societies in their home countries. In addition to         
providing comprehensive programs for students, CAP seeks to link institutions of      
higher education in the United States with their counterparts in grantees' home        
countries.                                                                                                               
<P>                                                                                                             
                                                                  
<H3><FONT COLOR=#004080> A LETTER FROM THE DEPUTY DIRECTOR </FONT></H3>                
<P>                    
Greetings to the extended family of CAP grantees current and past,   
to campus staff on both sides of the Atlantic, and to our colleagues at the national foundations.  I would      
like to introduce the first edition of NewsCAP, the Virtual University's newsletter, with a few remarks on           
our goals and intentions in creating this publication, as well as a summary of the current edition's contents.   
 <P>                                                          
While academic exchange is not the sole cure for global ills, it is an excellent mechanism for promoting           
intellectual curiosity over traditional animosity, understanding over prejudice, and sympathy over             
judgment. To these ends, CAP fellowships are centered in the Virtual University, a concept which refers to            
a range of activities designed to create a sense of community and shared interest amongst students             
participating in CAP programs. Our goal is to encourage thoughtful discussions of topics outside of          
standard academic curricula but relevant to the students' home countries.   
<P>                                                                        
Virtual University programming offers a variety of opportunities for students and faculty from diverse             
backgrounds to share ideas and experiences outside of traditional academic structures. Activities include          
summer orientation workshops, program staff sessions with grantees and faculty at host universities, winter                  
conferences, and the spring scholarship meeting for overseas staff involved in CAP programs. These events              
afford grantees, university personnel, and foundation staff the opportunity to meet and discuss issues face-           
to-face. With this newsletter, we provide an additional forum for sharing perspectives.   
<P>                                                                        
We currently plan to issue NewsCAP three times a year. The first few issues will focus on a current CAP                
program, describing its origin, intent, and scope. We will highlight grantees who have distinguished         
themselves during their fellowship or afterwards in their home country. We will also spotlight one or more             
of the national foundations associated with the Open Society Institute, preferably with submissions from                     
foundation staff. Updates on programs, alumni activity, Internet discussion group opportunities, and other                   
topics of interest will also be regular features. We welcome any kind of submission from our readers, be it     
commentary on an issue related to a specific field, questions regarding program policies or guidelines,   
information on activities of interest to the international student community, creative writing, or descriptions            
of amusing or thought-provoking experiences related to intercultural interaction. (Submissions for         
NewsCAP should be forwarded to Kristin Crosby, Student Service Manager, at kcrosbsy@sorosny.org or   
fax (212) 974 0367.   
      
This issue of NewsCAP highlights the Supplementary Grant Program for Students from the former                
Yugoslavia, CAP's largest fellowship program. The program is described in "Preserving The Mosaic," and              
is followed by an essay written by a program grantee. Helpful insights into applying for grants are offered                
by Janet Davidson, one of our selection committee members. We've also included reports from staff on            
various CAP-related activities, and brief updates on current or new programs.   
<P>             
A wealth of topics are generated by events in the countries with which we are all associated.  I hope our                      
readers will use NewsCAP as a forum for discussion as much as a source of information.  Your thoughts           
and ideas are critical to creating a lively and instructive dialogue, and we look forward to hearing from all           
of you. Welcome!                                          
<P>               
<FONT SIZE=-1><I>--Martha Loerke </I></FONT>        
<P>                
<P>     
