<HTML>                                                                                                                 
<HEAD>                                                                                                                 
<TITLE>NewsCAP</TITLE>                                                                                                                 
</HEAD>                                                                                                                 
<BODY BGCOLOR ="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#F50A2B" VLINK="#1F8F5F"                                    
ALINK="#FFFFFF">                  
<CENTER>                                          
<FONT COLOR=#004080><H2>Virtual University NewsCAP</H2>           
</CENTER>                                    
<P>                                                                       
<H3> TIPS FOR GRANT APPLICANTS</H3> </FONT>                                                                                                                     
<P>                                                                                                                 
<IMG ALIGN=left SRC="zdrav.jpg" HEIGHT= 175 WIDTH=250>                                                                         
<P>                                                                                                              
<FONT SIZE=+2><B>A</B></FONT>ttending university in the United States is an expensive                                                                          
undertaking for any student.  For students from other countries, higher education in the United States is                                                                          
often possible only with the assistance of hard-working and generous parents or under the sponsorship of a                                                                          
government, a university, or a sympathetic foundation. As costs rise and competition for limited funds                                                                          
increases, more and more students are applying for grant funds to help finance their studies.                                                                          
<P>                                                                         
Grants, unlike loans, generally don't need to be repaid, as long as grantees fulfill grant conditions.                                              
Conditions include such things as maintaining enrollment at an accredited institution and using the funds                                                                          
for the specified purpose.  Agencies can ask that the money be returned if it is shown later that fraud or                                                                          
deceit was used in making application for the grant.                                                                          
<P>                                                                         
Grantors often want to encourage study of a particular subject, to assist a particular group of people, or to                                                                          
promote education in a particular location. The aims and purposes of a grant and the philosophy of the                                                                          
funding agency is usually described in the information which accompanies application forms.                                                                          
<P>                                                                         
Applying for grants can be confusing.  Knowing a little bit about that process can help you maximize your                                                                          
chances for success.  Too often, students' grant applications are not seriously considered because the                                                                          
paperwork is carelessly or inappropriately prepared.  Following is a list of suggestions that can help ensure                                                                          
that your application will get the attention that it deserves.                                                                          
<P>                                                                         
<FONT SIZE=+3 COLOR=#F50A2B><B>1.</B></FONT>  Be sure you understand the purpose and the                   
conditions of the grant. Make a list of                                         
the criteria which determine eligibility.  Are you eligible?  If you do not meet the eligibility requirements,    
you are probably wasting your time by applying.  Spend that time looking for  other grants for which you    
do qualify. Some of the most commonly listed conditions include:                                                                           
<P>                                                                         
<LI><I>Currently enrolled student. . .</I>  If a grantor requires students to be currently enrolled in classes,    
your application will not be considered if you are not planning to begin your studies until the following                                             
year.</LI>                                            
<P>                                                                         
<LI><I>Age range between. . .</I>  If the grantor specifies an age range and you fall within that range,    
fine. If not, it is worth a phone call to the granting agency to see if exceptions will be made. If you apply as    
an exception, it is even more important to present a convincing argument that you are particularly needy    
and deserving of support.</LI>                                            
<P>                                                                         
<LI><I>Upper division, graduate studies, academic studies, students of the humanities, etc. . .</I>    
Sometimes grantors want to narrow the range of applicants to a particular level of education or to a specific    
field of study.  If you don't meet the requirement, don't apply.</LI>                                            
<P>                                                                         
<LI>'Planning to return to the home country. . . 'If the grantor wants to limit support to those who intend to                                                                          
return to their home country, and you are clearly preparing to settle permanently in the United States, look                                                                          
for other opportunities. If you are planning to return home, make it clear in your application how you can                                                                          
use your educational experience in the United States to improve conditions in your country.</LI>                                                                     
<P>                                                                         
<FONT SIZE=+3 COLOR=#F50A2B><B>2.</B></FONT>  Photocopy application forms before you                  
begin to fill them in. Use the copy as a                                         
rough draft.  After you have penciled in and reviewed your answers with an adviser (#9), transfer your                                         
answers to the final form.                                                                          
<P>                                                                         
<FONT SIZE=+3 COLOR=#F50A2B><B>3.</B></FONT>  Read directions carefully and follow them                  
exactly as you complete the grant                                         
application. If the directions tell you to type or use black ink, don't fill out the form in green ink or with a                                         
pencil. Even minor departures from stated rules can cause an application to be disqualified.                                                                          
<P>                                                                         
<FONT SIZE=+3 COLOR=#F50A2B><B>4.</B></FONT>  Be sure to include all requested                  
documentation. If current transcripts are requested,                                         
include them; do the same with letters of recommendation. If proof of your expenses is requested,                                         
photocopy receipts or canceled checks and include the photocopies with your application. If you feel the                                             
documentation somehow presents an inaccurate view of your situation, include the documentation but                                             
clarify it. For example, if your GPA is lower than you think is acceptable, explain the reasons for your                                             
difficulties. Was your English too weak to convey your understanding of the material? Were job                                             
responsibilities detracting from your study time?  Explain the difficulty and tell how you managed to                                             
overcome the problem.                                            
<P>                                                                         
<FONT SIZE=+3 COLOR=#F50A2B><B>5.</B></FONT>  If you have questions about the grant or the                  
application process, re-read the                                         
information you have received. The answer to your question is probably contained in the application                                         
packet. If, after reading the packet again, you still have questions, ask your school adviser for help. A                                         
phone call to the granting agency may be necessary, but be careful about pestering the office with frequent                                         
or unnecessary calls.                                                                          
<P>                                                                         
<FONT SIZE=+3 COLOR=#F50A2B><B>6.</B></FONT>  When a grant requires matching funds,                  
explain where additional money will be                                         
found.  If you have a tuition waiver, mention it. If your room and board are provided by an uncle, mention                                         
it. If you expect to work during the school year, say so. Most grants cannot provide enough money for all                                         
your expenses, but a grantor may be able to come up with a couple of thousand dollars to help meet some                                         
of the extra costs of an education. Remember that the purpose of the grant is to fund educational expenses.                                         
If the grantor knows that your room and food are provided, the money could help you with tuition or books                                         
and transportation costs. If the grantor knows your other expenses are taken care of, the grant can help                                         
reduce the amount of time you need to work.                                                                          
<P>                                                                         
<FONT SIZE=+3 COLOR=#F50A2B><B>7.</B></FONT>  Do not rely on school advisers, friends, or                  
relatives to get a grant for you from the                                         
granting agency. The awarding of grants in the United States is increasingly competitive and more and                                         
more impersonal.  Selection committees consider applications on their own merit, regardless of any outside                                             
information about the applicant that might become known. For this reason, you should prepare your                                             
application carefully and completely.  Committee members may have preferences for certain schools,                                             
subjects, even countries, but it is considered unethical by US standards to advocate the awarding of a grant                                             
to a student based on friendship or family ties. Because you cannot rely on a special friend advocating for                                             
you, you must be sure that your application is well-prepared and complete.                                                                           
<P>                                                                         
If you are shy about telling the committee how deserving you are, ask for letters of recommendation from                                                                          
teachers, advisers, host families, church sponsors, or others. and include those letters with your application                                                                          
when you mail it.                                                                          
<P>                                                                         
<FONT SIZE=+3 COLOR=#F50A2B><B>8.</B></FONT>  Remember that Americans value and want to                
reward individual initiative, self-help, honesty, and service to others.  If you have volunteered your    
services to the community, if you have persevered in the face of failure and succeeded, be sure mention of    
your accomplishments is included in your application.  An effective way to do this is through the letters of    
recommendation written by others who know of your success.                                                                          
<P>               
<FONT SIZE=+3 COLOR=#F50A2B><B>9.</B></FONT>  Pretend you do not know who wrote your                
application: does it present a full and true story of your situation? Do you have all necessary    
documentation?  Are questions answered completely?  If your English skills are weak, have you kept    
control of your writing through simple, brief, accurate sentences and explanations?  (While you may, of    
course, get assistance as you fill out the application, it should be your application' filled out using your    
words' and not the work of a friend or relative.)  Proofread carefully!                                                                          
<P>                                                                         
<FONT SIZE=+3 COLOR=#F50A2B><B>10.</B></FONT>  When everything is complete, assemble the                
documentation and attach it to the application.  Double-check to be sure you are including all required       
materials. Make photocopies of everything for your own file.  Use an envelope that is large enough to       
accommodate your application neatly. Address it neatly and accurately. Be sure to time the mailing of your       
application correctly so that it reaches its destination several days before the due date. You don't want all       
your hard work disqualified because it arrived too late!                                                                          
<P>                                                                         
Finding funds to help pay for education is difficult and very competitive. There are many good, deserving                                                                          
students who will be applying along with you for limited funds.  Even if you are not successful in your                                                                          
application, don't give up. Use the coming year to gather evidence and support for your next application.                                                                          
Good luck!                                                                         
<BR>                                                                         
<FONT SIZE=-1><I>Janet Davidson</I></FONT>                                                                         
<P>                                                                                                        
