ALINK="#FFFFFF">                  
<CENTER>                                            
<FONT COLOR=#004080><H2>Virtual University NewsCAP</H2> </FONT>                         
</CENTER>                                      
<P>                                                                         
<H3><FONT COLOR=#004080>PROGRAM BRIEFS</FONT></H3>                                                                          
<P>                                                                                                           
<IMG ALIGN=left SRC="tower.jpg" HEIGH=280 WIDTH=175 BORDER=2><H4>Virtual University          
Exchange           
Programs</H4>                                                                          
<P>                                                                          
The Virtual University Undergraduate Exchange program offers undergraduates from Central and Eastern                                                                           
Europe, Ukraine, and the Baltic States one year of study at a college or university in the United States.                                                                            
Grants are awarded to third- and fourth-year students who will return to their home institutions to complete                                                                           
their degrees.  The Virtual University Graduate Exchange Program offers one year of doctoral research in                                                                           
the United States to Ph.D. candidates from Central and Eastern Europe. Fields of study are concentrated in                                                                           
the social sciences and humanities. Fellowships are funded in part by the US Agency for International                                                                           
Development.                                                                            
<P>                                                                          
More than 500 students competed for 50 undergraduate and 20 graduate places for the 1995/96 fellowship                                                                           
year. The undergraduate class, representing 14 countries, will attend an orientation in Prague from July 23-                                                                          
27, designed to prepare them for the academic rigors of the American classroom.  During the five days,                                                                           
they will take four classes: political philosophy, post-war American history, American literature, and                                                                           
expository writing.                                                                            
<P>                                                                         
<P>                                         
<H4>AUBG Scholarships </H4>                                                                          
<P>                                                                          
Each year CAP awards 20 scholarships for four years of undergraduate study at the American University in                                                                           
Bulgaria. Students come from Albania, Belarus, Georgia, Kazakstan, Macedonia, Moldova, Poland,                                                                           
Romania, and Yugoslavia. Including the incoming class of 20 grantees, 86 students currently attending                                                                           
AUBG are sponsored by CAP. The American niversity in Bulgaria is located in Blagoevgrad and was                                                                           
started in 1991 as an alternative educational institution for students in the region. The curriculum and                                                                           
teaching methods employed in the university closely follow the American model. All instruction is in                                                                           
English.                                                                           
<P>                
<FONT SIZE=-1><B>Related Links</B></FONT><BR>                  
<A HREF="http://www.aubg.edu/">AUBG</A>     
<P>                 
<IMG ALIGN=left SRC=statue.jpg HEIGHT=125 WIDTH=100><H4>Supplementary Grants for                                                                  
Burma</H4>                                                                          
<P>                                                                          
The Supplementary Grant Program for Students from Burma was created in 1994 and gave 70 awards in its                                                                           
first year. Grants are intended primarily, but not exclusively, for refugee university students who actively                                                                           
participated in the pro-democracy movement of 1988 and whose education was subsequently disrupted.                                                                            
The Consortium received 474 applications for the 1995/96 program and awarded 170 grants.                                                                           
<P>                    
<P>                  
<FONT SIZE=-1><B>Related Links</B></FONT><BR>                  
<A HREF="http://sunsite.unc.edu/freeburma/freeburma.html">FreeBurma </A><BR>                  
<A HREF="http://sunsite.nus.sg/SEAlinks/burma-info.html">Burma Information</A><BR>                  
<P>                  
<H4> CEU & New Economics School Scholarships</H4>                                                                          
<P>                                                                          
Graduates of the Central European University are eligible for scholarships for one year of doctoral study in                                                                      
the United States or Western Europe. More than 50 students will receive awards for study beginning this                                                                      
fall. The Consortium also provides a small number of awards to allow students from the New Economics                                                                      
School in Moscow to pursue doctoral study in the United States.                                                                           
<P>                                                                          
<IMG ALIGN=left SRC=castle.jpg HEIGHT=175 WIDTH=175><H4> UK Scholarships </H4>                                                                          
<P>                                                                          
The Consortium offers one-year scholarships for scholars from Central and Eastern Europe                                                                           
and the Newly Independent and Baltic States to study at several institutions in England. Partial funding is                                                                           
received from the British Foreign and Commonwealth Office. Recruitment takes place in the fall of each                                                                           
year for the next academic year. Applicants must be in the home country at the time of application. This                                                                           
fall, 55 students will be studying under various programs at the following schools: Oxford University,                                                                           
Cambridge University, University of Manchester, and University of Warwick.                                                                           
<P>                                                                          
<H4> Edmund S. Muskie and FSA Fellowships</H4>                                                                          
<P>                                                                          
In response to the dissolution of the former Soviet Union, the United States Congress created the Edmund                                                                           
S. Muskie and Freedom Support Act Fellowship programs to support the economic and democratic                                                                           
development of that region. The program provides fellowships to qualified citizens of the Newly                                                                           
Independent and Baltic States for one year of graduate study at accredited institutions of higher education                                                                           
in the United States.                                                                            
<P>                                                                          
The program is funded by the United States Information Agency and is administered on its behalf by CAP,                                                                           
the American Council of Teachers of Russian, the Institute of International Education, and the International                                                                           
Research and Exchanges Board. Consortium fellowships are awarded for study in law, public                                                                           
administration, and education administration, and include practical training for up to 12 weeks after                                                                           
completion of the program.                                                                           
<P>                                                                          
During the 1994/95 academic year, CAP supported 53 students, many of whom are currently engaged in                                                                           
summer internships.  Some of the more interesting internships include: research on criminal law reform in                                                                           
Russia at Columbia University School of Law, work at the United Nations Division for the Advancement                                                                           
of Women, and training at Price Waterhouse's international business development department. Consortium                                                                           
staff are preparing for the arrival of 96 grantees this summer for the 1995/96 academic year.                                                                           
<P>                 
<FONT SIZE=-1><B>Related Links</B></FONT><BR>                  
<A HREF="http://www.usia.gov/">USIA</A><BR>                  
<A HREF="#gopher://info.irex.org/">IREX</A><BR>                  
<P>                
<P>                                                                   
<IMG ALIGN=left SRC=bluswrl.jpg HEIGHT=120 WIDTH=120><H4> New Initiatives </H4>                                                                          
<P>                                                                          
Apart from the established programs, CAP periodically awards institutional grants for new initiatives or                                                                           
pilot programs that may be expanded in future years. The College of Law in London, for example, received                                                                           
a grant to support five students from Albania in the study of law. Should the program prove useful,                                                                           
fellowships may be offered elsewhere in the Balkans in the future.                                                                          
<P>                                                                          
Another grant went to The New School for Social Research in New York to fund five students to attend the                                                                           
Democracy and Diversity Institute's summer conference in Cracow, Poland. The conference will focus on                                                                           
economic and constitutional reform, and the social construction of gender.                                                                            
<P>                                                                          
A grant was also awarded to Indiana University to implement a workshop for refugee Burmese students,                                                                           
including students from CAP's Supplementary Grants for Burma. According to Ken Rogers, Associate                                                                           
Dean and Director of the Office of International Programs at the university, the workshop 'will enable                                                                           
refugee students to discuss their current needs and concerns with regard to their present educational                                                                           
objectives and will also help them to think about the future.' Over 100 students are expected to attend.                                                                           
                                                                           
<A NAME="staff">
<HR SIZE=2>                                                                     
<FONT COLOR=#004080><H3>STAFF REPORTS</H2></FONT>                     
<P>                                                                          
<IMG ALIGN=left SRC=buda.gif HEIGHT=225 WIDTH=350><H4> CAP in Budapest </H4>                                                                          
<P>                                                                          
A conference held in Budapest in early May marked the first time scholarship coordinators from                                                                           
throughout the network of independent Soros-sponsored foundations gathered to discuss current and future                                                                           
scholarship programs. Forty-five people from 22 foundations, the CAP, the CEU, Oxford University, the                                                                           
American University in Bulgaria, and the Civic Education Project attended the conference from 11-12                                                                           
May.  The first day began with welcoming remarks from OSI Vice President for Programs Karen J.                                                                           
Greenberg. CAP Deputy Director Martha Loerke opened the conference by  introducing the CAP staff                                                                           
from New York. Coordinators from the national foundations then introduced themselves.                                                                           
<P>                                                                          
Participants then reported on the state of higher education in their countries and commented on the                                                                           
challenges they face administering scholarship programs. In her report on Lithuania, Audrone Uzieliene,                                                                           
the director of the Educational Advising Center in Vilnius, stated that the transition from Soviet to                                                                           
independent rule had both positive and negative effects on higher education.  Positive effects included                                                                           
increased academic freedom and a concomitant rise in enrollments.  On the down side, state financial                                                                           
assistance for higher education continues to decline and decentralization has resulted in somewhat                                                                           
incoherent policy making.                                                                           
<P>                                                                          
Hazim Kasic, from the Open Society Fund - Bosnia & Herzegovina, reflected upon the conflicting                                                                           
emotions about education and study abroad brought on by the war.  Specifically, he commented that the                                                                           
Supplementary Grant Program for the Former Yugoslavia is perceived in Bosnia as a reward to students                                                                           
who have left Bosnia. Dr. Greenberg commented that OSI is trying to balance Kasic's concerns with a                                                                           
desire to assist students displaced by war. Above all, Dr. Greenberg emphasized, both perspectives offer                                                                           
valid points for serious discussion.  In the afternoon, three workshops focused on the Muskie/Freedom                                                                           
Support Act Fellowships, the Virtual University Exchange Programs, and Western European Scholarships.                                                                           
Each workshop provided participants with the opportunity to brainstorm about more efficient ways to                                                                           
administer programs as well as solve more immediate problems.                                                                            
<P>                                                                          
At the workshop on Western European scholarships, CAP Assistant Director Amy Yenkin addressed                                                                           
questions on how and why countries are selected for programs in the United Kingdom.  Yenkin                                                                           
commented that as important as equity is (insuring that all countries have a chance to participate), it is also                                                                           
important that programs be needed in a given country.  She added that OSI hoped to expand fellowship                                                                           
schemes in the United Kingdom to the University of Edinburgh and the London School of Economics.                                                                            
Decisions about these schools will be made later this summer.                                                                           
<P>                                                                          
The second day of the workshop was devoted to improving network communication, program evaluation,                                                                           
alumni tracking, and a discussion of the challenges CAP program administrators face in balancing grantee                                                                           
needs with program policies and regulations. Conference participants received a report on all of the                                                                           
scholarship programs funded by the foundation network.  In total, the network supports roughly 6,500                                                                           
students through more than 170 different programs that have made roughly $12 million in grants.                                                                           
<P>                                                                          
<IMG ALIGN=left SRC=worldmap.jpg><H4>Advising Centers</H4>                                                                          
<P>                                                                          
                                                                          
The recent OSEAS conference held in Athens, Greece from 1-5 July brought together overseas advisors                                                                           
from 45 countries to discuss the profession of educational advising. More than 30 representatives from                                                                           
Soros-sponsored advising centers attended the conference. Several representatives presented comments on                                                                           
various panels. Audrone Uzieliene, Lithuania, gave a talk entitled 'Survival Management for Busy                                                                           
Advising Centers,' Ivan Tsarikov, Belarus, was a panelist for a session on advising issues in the Newly                                                                           
Independent States, Marvi Pulver, Estonia,  and Dace Sinkevica, Latvia, offered their perspectives on the                                                                           
use of technology at advising centers, which was the overall theme of the conference. Martha Henry of the                                                                           
CEU Advising Center in Prague and Program Coordinator for Advising Centers Ami Golden, also attended                                                                           
the conference and presented reports at a session entitled 'Sponsored Programs in Times of Political                                                                           
Change.'                                                                           
<P>                                                                          
'The conference provided an excellent opportunity for our advisers to get to know one another and gave us                                                                           
the chance to foster closer working relationships.' said Golden.  'It was also an ideal time to establish                                                                           
relationships  with other overseas advisers and university professionals.'                                                                            
<P>                                                                          
Golden is currently working on a report which will include additional commentary on the conference and                                                                           
which will also discuss the many issues she encountered during site visits to several advising centers this                                                                           
spring. One attitude she encountered at every stop was great appreciation from local professors, non-profit                                                                           
organizations, and USIS officials for the efforts of the local Soros educational advisers.  Congratulations to                                                                           
all for work well done!                                                                           
<P>                                      
<H4>NAFSA Conference</H4>                                                                          
<P>                                                                          
Several CAP staff members attended a conference in New Orleans sponsored by NAFSA:  Association of                                                                           
International Educators. The conference attracted over 3,600 professionals from the field of international                                                                           
educational exchange. The title of the week-long conference was 'Realities and Responses:  Navigating                                                                           
Change in International Education.' Consortium staff attended workshops focusing on pre-departure                                                                           
orientation, women and social change in Eastern Europe, the Russian educational system, and visa issues.                                                                           
<P>                                                                          
With colleagues from the Rockefeller, Ford, and Kellogg foundations, CAP Assistant Director Amy                                                                           
Yenkin sat on a panel entitled 'Foundations as Sponsors of International Students.' They discussed the role                                                                           
of foundations in sponsoring students from developing countries and what responsibilities, if any,                                                                           
universities have to sponsors.                                                                            
<P>                                                                          
Educational advisors Ivan Tsarikov and Natalia Kamenkova from Belarus, Martha Henry from the Czech                                                                           
Republic, Lucinia Ball from Romania, Alexander Makarenko from Ukraine, and Marvi Pulver and Eha                                                                           
Teder from Estonia attended a dinner hosted by the CAP staff members from the New York office.                                                                           
<P>                                                                          
At a time when international education is facing serious federal budget cuts, CAP should consider how it                                                                           
can help fill the gap.  The conference provided CAP staff with the opportunity to discover how the field of                                                                            
international education is changing, what needs international students have, and how CAP can work more                                                                           
closely with universities to insure the continued development of international educational initiatives.                                                                           
<P>                
<FONT SIZE=-1><B>Related Links</B></FONT><BR>                  
<A HREF="http://stolaf.edu/people/cdr/nafsa">NAFSA</A><BR>                  
<A HREF="http://www.csc.fi/forum">International Education Forum</A><BR>                  
<P>                
<P>                           
