<title> Upcoming Uzbek Cultural Events  
</title>   
</head>   
<body bgcolor="FFFFFF">   
<table border=0 cellpadding=6>   
<tr>   
<td><h1>   
Upcoming Uzbek Cultural Events </h1></td></table>   

<p>
<h2>Suzani : Embroideries from the Oases of Central Asia (Through February 23, 1997) </h2>
Large, colorful, boldly patterned embroideries from Central Asia known as suzani (from the Persian term 
for needlework) are on display. Suzani
embroideries, used as wall hangings and bedcovers, were made by girls and women for their dowries in the 
cities and towns of present-day
Uzbekistan and Tadzhikistan. This exhibit features 11 19th-century suzani embroideries from the collection 
of Russel S. Fling. 
<p>
Mon-Sat 10am-5pm; Sun 1-5pm <br>
Admission: Suggested donation $5 <br>
Textile Museum <br>
2320 S St. N.W. at Massachusetts Avenue <br>
Tel. 667-0441<br>
<p>
<h2>Legacy of Uzbekistan's Silk Roads (Through December 1, 1996) </h2>

Part of UNESCO's Silk Road project, this exhibition shows more than 1,000 objects from over 16 centuries 
of silk trade in the region that is
modern Uzbekistan. The area's inhabitants occupied a strategic position at the intersection of the Chinese, 
Indian, Near Eastern and European
civilizations, and consequently played a pivotal role not only in the trade of silk and other luxuries, but in 
cultural exchanges as well.
<p>
Tue-Fri 9am-5pm; Sat, Sun 10am-5pm <br>
Museum fuer Voelkerkunde <br>
8 Lansstrasse <br>
Dahlem. U-Bahn: Dahlem-Dorf. Bus: 110, 180 <br>
Tel. 83 011<br>
<p> 
