<html> 
<head> 
<title>About The Lindesmith Center</title> 
</head> 
<body bgcolor="FFFFFF" link="006699" vlink="339999" text="000000">
<center><h4>THE LINDESMITH CENTER</h4></center> 
<center><img align=middle src=line.gif width=600 alt=#></center> 
<center><h2>About The Lindesmith Center</h2></center>
<p>
<b>The Lindesmith Center</b> is a policy research institute founded in 1994 that focuses on broadening the 
debate on drug policy and related issues. The center houses a library and information center, organizes 
seminars and conferences, acts as a link between scholars, government and the media, directs a grants program 
in central and eastern Europe and undertakes projects on special topics such as methadone policy reform and 
alternatives to drug testing in the workplace. The guiding principle of the center is harm reduction, an 
alternative approach to drug policy and treatment that focuses on minimizing the adverse effects of both drug 
use and drug prohibition. Particular attention is focused on analyzing the experiences of foreign countries in 
reducing drug-related harms.
 <p>
<b>The Lindesmith Center</b> addresses issues of drug policy reform through a variety of projects:
<p>

<i><b>Drug Policy Seminar Series.</b></i> Seminars and panel discussions are generally open to the public 
and include time for questions and debate. Recent seminars have included: 
<ul>
<li>Andrew Weil on "Coffee, Coca, Cola, Chocolate: A Dispassionate Look at Stimulant Plants"
<li>Ueli Locher on "Switzerland's Heroin Prescription Experiment"
<li>John DiIulio on "Civil Society, Violent Crime, and the War on Drugs"
<li>Rafael Pardo and Fernando Cepeda, former Colombian cabinet ministers, on "U.S. Drug Policy in South 
America"
<li>A series of eight special seminars given by doctors, researchers and social workers on "Drug Treatment 
Reconsidered: Harm Reduction Perspectives"
</ul><p>
<i><b>International Harm Reduction Development Program.</b></i> This program matches experienced 
mentors from Europe and the United States with fledgling public health initiatives in Central and Eastern 
Europe. Twenty-nine grants were made last year for projects such as needle exchanges, methadone treatment 
programs, drop-in centers and training seminars. 
<p>
<i><b>The Lindesmith Center Library.</b></i> Our rapidly growing library is one of the largest collections 
on drugs and drug policy in the world. It contains over 10,000 books, reports, government documents, 
periodicals, videos, and articles from the U.S. and abroad as well as in-depth collections on drug related 
policies in Canada, Latin America, Great Britain, Germany, the Netherlands, Switzerland, and Australia. We 
also maintain an electronic site on the World Wide Web that provides access to hundreds of documents from 
our permanent collection and the latest news from the Center as well as links to other relevant web-sites. 
<i>(Web Address: http://www.soros.org/lindesmith/tlcmain.html)</i>
<p>
<i><b>Methadone Policy Reform Project.</b></i> This program examines harm reduction approaches to 
methadone treatment, with particular emphasis on the experiences of Europe and Australia, and informs the 
public and policy makers about effective alternative approaches to methadone provision. Members of the 
Center collaborate with methadone advocacy groups, researchers at Montefiore and Beth Israel Medical 
Centers and drug treatment providers. 
<p>
<i><b>Publications.</b></i> The Lindesmith Center produces regularly updated fact sheets on topics 
including Needle and Syringe Availability, Drug Prohibition and the U.S. Prison System, Drug Education, and 
Methadone Maintenance Treatment. The Center also publishes monographs, including "Exposing Marijuana 
Myths: A Review of the Scientific Evidence," by sociologist Lynn Zimmer and pharmacologist John P. 
Morgan. A new project will re-issue a series of out-of-print "classics" in the field of drug policy. We also offer 
modest support for scholarly works on the history of drugs and drug policy.
<p>
<i><b>"Lindesmith West."</b></i> In 1996 the Center opened an office in San Francisco directed by Marsha 
Rosenbaum, Ph.D, a National Institute on Drug Abuse grantee for 18 years, and author of <i>Women on 
Heroin</i>, and (with Jerome Beck) <i>The MDMA Experience</i> as well as numerous pamphlets and 
scholarly articles on drug use, drug abuse, drug education, women's issues and drug treatment.
<p>	
<b>The Lindesmith Center</b> is a project of the Open Society Institute (OSI), which promotes the 
development of open societies around the world through projects relating to education, media, legal reform 
and human rights. OSI was founded by George Soros, who is involved in extensive philanthropic activities. 
The Center's director is Ethan Nadelmann, J.D., Ph.D., author of <i>Cops Across Borders: The 
Internationalization of U.S. Criminal Law Enforcement</i> (Penn State Press, 1993) and many articles in 
scholarly and popular journals. Dr. Nadelmann has taught Political Science and Public Affairs at Harvard and 
Princeton Universities and has lectured throughout the world on drug policy and international law 
enforcement. The Center is named for Alfred Lindesmith, one of the first scholars to challenge conventional 
thinking on drug policy.
<p>
	<center><i>For further information, contact Ethan Nadelmann or Communications Director 
Sharon Herbstman at (212)887-0695<br>
888 7th Ave., Suite 2700, New York, NY 10106<br>
E-mail <a href="mailto:enadelmann@sorosny.org">enadelmann@sorosny.org</a> or <a 
href="mailto:sherbstman@sorosny.org">sherbstman@sorosny.org</a><br>
Web Address <a href="http://www.lindesmith.org">http://www.lindesmith.org</a><br>
<p>

For information about The San Francisco office, contact Marsha Rosenbaum (415)921-4987<br>
E-mail <a href="mailto:marsharose@aol.com">marsharose@aol.com</a></i></center>
