<html> 
<head> 
<title>Methadone Treatment by GPs in Amsterdam (The Lindesmith Center)</title> 
</head> 
<body bgcolor="FFFFFF" link="006699" vlink="339999" text="000000">
<center><h4>THE 
LINDESMITH CENTER</h4></center> 
<center><img align=middle src=line.gif width=600 alt=#></center><br> 
 
<center><h3>Methadone Treatment by General Practitioners in Amsterdam</h3></center> 
<p> 
<font size=2><i>van Brussel, Giel. "Methadone Treatment by General<br> 
Practitioners in Amsterdam." <b>Bulletin of the New York <br> 
Academy of Medicine</b> 72 (1995):348-358.</i></font> 
<hr>
<center><font size=2><i>This document has been reprinted electronically by permission. All rights 
reserved.</i></font></center><hr> 
<p> 
<blockquote> 
<b> 
Abstract:</b> In Amsterdam, a three-tiered program exists to deal with drug use and addiction. 
General practitioners form the backbone of the system, helping to deal with the majority of 
addicts, who are not criminals and many of whom desire to be free of addiction. Distinctions are 
made between drugs with "acceptable" and 'unacceptable', risks, and between drug use and drug- 
related crime; patients who fall into the former categories air treated in a nonconfrontational, 
nonstigmatizing manner; such a system helps prevent ,the ,majority of Patients from passing into 
unacceptable, criminalized categories. The overall program has demonstrated harm reduction 
both for patients and for the city of Amsterdam.</blockquote> 
 
 
 
<p>Amsterdam is the capital of the Netherlands. With 700,000 inhabitants, it is a relatively 
small and compact city. Nevertheless, in the last 20 years it has seen a major drug epidemic. 
Since 1981, methadone has been provided on a large scale-even to active drug users-without 
requiring strict preconditions, and is received by about 80% of the legal drug users living in 
Amsterdam. This treatment Is partly carried out by the large-scale programs of an organization 
known in Amsterdam as the Gemeentelijke Geneeskundige & Gezondheids Dienst (GG&GD), a 
municipal health organization that provides public health services aimed at prevention, such as 
vaccinations, STD clinics, ambulance transport, forensic medical services, and social psychiatric 
care. Approximately 40% of the total methadone prescriptions in the city are handled by the 
city's general practitioners. 
<p>Particularly noticeable in the development of the drug epidemic of the last 20 years is the fact 
that the whole drug-user population has stabilized as a result of the limited influx of new users 
and the long survival time of the residual group of those chronically addicted. Amsterdam 
occupies an exceptional position in the general Dutch policy on drugs because of the role played 
by general practitioners in the provision of services to drug users. 
<p> 
<b>The Amsterdam Drug Epidemic(1,2)</b> 
 
<p>Amsterdam was the first city in Holland to see heroin use. The drug was introduced in 1972 
by American Vietnam War deserters. The arrival of heroin coincided with a scarcity of opium, 
caused by the mass deportation of illegally resident Chinese. As a result, a group of about 150 
people, who by the end of the 1960s, had become addicted to semirefined injectable opium, 
changed to the then still relatively cheap heroin. 
<p>In 1974, there emerged a second and even larger wave of heroin users among young men 
who had recently emigrated to the Netherlands from Surinam. When Surinam gained 
independence from the Netherlands, half of the country's population chose to remain Dutch and 
had, therefore, to emigrate to the fog and rain of western Europe. Some 2,000 of the 
young Surinamese immigrants in Amsterdam rapidly became addicted; 90% of them were men. 
They had a strong dislike of injection and preferred to smoke the heroin from heated aluminum 
foil ("chasing the dragon"). 
<p>A third wave of heroin users arrived in 1976 and 1977. These were, for the most part, 
socially less well-endowed young Dutch people from the native population of Amsterdam. 
Again, the majority-60-were male. Half of the latter group elected intravenous use; the other half 
adopted the Surinamese practice. An additional problem was the large number of illegally 
resident foreign drug users-principally Germans-who regarded Amsterdam as a sort of European 
Mecca for illegal drugs. Practically all in this group took heroin intravenously. By the start of 
the 1980s, this chaotic explosion in drug use was affecting an estimated 10,000 people and had 
created a political problem of the first order. This political aspect stimulated a large number of 
initiatives, of which the great majority failed, at least in part. The feeling of powerlessness that 
developed from this strongly influenced the development of drug-use policies. In particular, it 
seemed important to give effective, regulating help to active users who could not hope to make a 
fulfilling life for themselves without access to drugs. 
<p>The heroin epidemic peaked in 1984, stabilized, and went into regression until 1991, after 
which a slight increase was seen. At the present, a capture-recapture technique has allowed the 
Amsterdam drug-user population to be estimated at between 6,000 and 7,000 (Table 1). 
<p>For the majority of these people, there is evidence for combined use of heroin and cocaine, 
and for a restricted group--10% of the total--extreme abuse of alcohol and benzodiazepines. 
Heroin remains the most important substance used daily and on a large scale, but cocaine is used 
alongside it if money becomes available--from a welfare payment for instance. Cocaine is 
regularly used alongside heroin by street prostitutes and criminals. 
<p>If the users are divided according to ethnic group, about 40% are native white Dutch people: 
30% come from ethnic minorities (mostly Surinamese and most of the rest Moroccan); and 30% 
are foreign, of whom about half live legally in Amsterdam. The average age of the group has 
risen to 36. The "addiction career" of the Surinamese users lasts about 15 to 20 years; that for 
the native white Dutch and legal foreigners, between 10 and 15 years. The annual influx in the 
drug-user population is about 350 for native Dutch and ethnic minorities combined, and has been 
stable for many years. The outflow is made up of deaths-137 in 1993-and users who give up 
drugs more or less naturally. The latter group is mainly composed of the recent influx of addicts 
who have not become long-term users. One result of this dynamic is that the addict population 
of Amsterdam is becoming older and consequently more subject to illness and infirmity (Table 
II). 
<p>With respect to AIDS, there is a great difference in the infection and mortality rates of users 
from different ethnic groups. The difference has been attributed to the different ways of taking 
drugs within each group, with the ethnic minority users-who generally smoke their drugs- being 
much less exposed to infection than the largely i.v. drug-taking white Dutch and foreigners. This 
could help to explain the much lower total number of deaths (11 in 1993) among ethnic minority 
users. Among addicts in Amsterdam, AIDS is limited to i.v. drug users: the prevalence of HIV 
in this group since 1985 is 30%,(3) and the annual incidence of HIV infection in a cohort of 
Amsterdam multiproblem i.v. users for the last few years has been 3 %.(4) Another remarkable 
fact is the much lower prevalence of HIV among i.v. drug users in provincial Dutch cities such as 
Alkmaar, Arnhem, and Deventer, where it varies between 0% and 3%.(5) An estimated 1,280 
HIV-positive drug users are in Amsterdam, of which 725 had been identified as of January 1, 
1995. Approximately 270 HIV-positive drug users have died.(6) AIDS has manifested itself in 
the serious bacterial infections (pneumonia, endocarditis, tuberculosis) resulting from severe 
immunodeficiency. 
<p>Tuberculosis is a major threat to the public's health. In the past years, an effective approach 
has been established by integrating drug treatment, TBC screening, and treatment monitoring 
among drug users who have TB. As a result, the spread is contained (Table III). 
<p> 
<b>Dutch Amsterdam Drug Policy</b> 
 
<p>Drug policy in the Netherlands contains two dichotomies: (1) a distinction is made between 
drugs with acceptable risk (basically cannabis and cannabis products) and substances of 
unacceptable risk (heroin, cocaine, and amphetamines); and (2) a further distinction is made 
between drug use and drug-related crime. Drug use itself is a social and medical problem for 
which many forms of help are available, whether directed at abstinence or simple risk reduction. 
The latter is intended for those drug users-the majority-for whom total abstinence is not an 
option. Although society may wish to make this help available to drug users, unconditionally 
and without a waiting list, it cannot-and does not-turn a blind eye to the crimes the users commit. 
This becomes clear as some 1,000 members of Amsterdam's drug-user population are, at any one 
time, locked up in connection with drug-related crime; half of them for crimes against property, 
half for dealing, particularly street dealing. 
<p> 
<b>Prevention of Drug Use</b> 
<p>As a result of the distinction between hard and soft drugs, introduced by law in 1976, the 
social and cultural environments in which these types of drugs are used also have become, as it 
were, "uncoupled" In the Dutch perspective, cannabis is a pseudolegal drug, with which some 
30% of Amsterdam's teenagers have experimented. The use of cannabis among young people is 
limited in duration and frequency and in this manner plans no role in social marginalization. 
Instead, it manifests itself in brief, healthy experimentation. 
<p>Heroin is a street drug and, as such, is heavily stigmatized for young people. The facts 
underlying this attitude come out in the addiction biographies of new users. In 1993, 150 heroin 
users of both -white Dutch and ethnic minority backgrounds-whom at that time were not known 
to the GG&GD-were interviewed in the Amsterdam police cells.(7) Their average age was 28; 
all were heavily into crime and had experienced a failed education, both at elementary school and 
during "lower" (i.e., technical) secondary education. They were functionally illiterate despite 9 
years of schooling. For most young people such as these, cannabis use is established by the age 
of 15, at which age they also drop out of school as a result of the aforementioned illiteracy. 
Consequently, they become street criminals, get involved in the hard-drug scene through their 
commercial activities, start experimenting with heroin and cocaine around the age of 21, and 
within a year find they are hooked (Table IV). 
 
<p>Luckily, the number of people with in the Dutch welfare state who fall to the bottom of the 
education system in this way is very limited. They tend to comprise two broad groups: white 
Dutch people raised in classic antisocial environments (single parent, child abuse, alcoholism), 
and immigrants-particularly Moroccans--who have language problems and become alienated 
from the broader society. 
 
 
<p> 
<b>Medical and Social Services for Drug Addicts in Amsterdam: <br> 
Relationship Between the General Practitioner and the GG&GD</b> 
 
<p>There are two major aspects to these services: one consists of a broad and diverse system of 
clinics that provide residential treatment and ambulant care for drug users who wish to kick their 
habits. This differentiated treatment system is operated by the Jellinek Centre, which also 
operates a small American-type methadone program for abstinence-motivated drug users. The 
other major aspect is a low-threshold social-medical system for providing methadone to drug 
users. This aspect is handled by the GG&GD and by general practitioners. The GG&GD takes 
on the "difficult" clients, whereas the general practitioners deal with the already "well-regulated" 
ones sent to them by the GG&GD. 
<p>The Amsterdam treatment system differentiates between methods, treatment targets, and 
thresholds. The GG&GD provides, in principle, a "safety net" for all active drug users. A 
typical visible form of outreach in this aspect is the methadone bus. General practitioners serve 
socially regulated drug users who have stable patterns of addiction. The Jellinek Centre serves 
abstinence-motivated drug users; its efforts are aimed at stopping illegal drug use. 
<p> 
<i>GG&GD Programs</i> 
<p>GG&GD "safety net" programs service approximately 2,500 drug users per year. Great 
emphasis is placed on diagnostic protocols. The screening protocols are aimed at detecting a 
"good period" in a client's addiction career, and so referring him or her to the general practitioner 
for weekly methadone prescription or to the Jellinek Centre. To do this effectively, GG&GD 
programs are structured rigidly. The majority of the clients come daily, but with good social 
regulation of the client it is possible to change to a twice-weekly or even once-weekly provision. 
The mean dose of methadone is related to mode of drug use. For clients who consume drugs 
intravenously, it is 60 mg; clients who take drugs by mouth have a mean dose of 50 mg. The 
provision of methadone is linked to a package of medical help consisting of a thorough, protocol- 
directed examination every 3 months by a doctor and social worker. Besides evaluating current 
addiction status, great stress is placed on HIV prevention, safe drug use, and safe-sex techniques. 
The client's social situation also is investigated, and, if necessary, help is offered with such things 
as housing and managing welfare payments. Attempts are made to motivate clients to abstention 
treatment. Clients also are examined every 6 months for tuberculosis, and, for the HIV-positive 
clients, AIDS-drugs case management is offered. This involves monitoring the client's general 
medical condition and in particular the state of her or his immune system. The actual specialized 
HIV care takes place in Amsterdam hospitals. Clients also are monitored, inter alia, to determine 
if they keep their appointments at "polyclinics" (hospital outpatient departments, which may or 
may not be on the hospital site), to see if their medication is being properly used, and to detect 
any side effects early. At the moment, this system has succeeded in getting some 80% of 
Amsterdam's HIV-positive drug users to go to a polyclinic for early diagnosis and treatment. 
<p> 
<i>The General Practitioner</i> 
<p>The GP plays a central role in the Dutch health system. She or he is the one who sends the 
patient to the specialist, to a hospital, or to specialized treatment elsewhere. The GP is typically 
"the family doctor" for all complaints and illnesses of the family. The majority of Dutch people 
get their medical insurance through the "Ziekenfonds," a collective system run by the state. GPs 
have a variable number of state patients registered with them and receive a fixed fee of 180 
guilders a year for each one. Registration is done on a district basis. The GP system is, 
therefore, clearly based on the assumption that the great majority of registered patients are 
healthy and do not need the doctor's help. These healthy people compensate for the ones needing 
more medical care, such as the elderly, the chronically ill, and others. Most GPs are idealistically 
Motivated people, but not fools; the system depends on a large population of healthy people not 
presenting themselves for medical care by the GP. 
<p>A unique feature of care for drug users in Amsterdam is that the GP also is the first person an 
addict will deal with. In practice, this means that the GP will send the drug user to the GG&GD 
programs for diagnosis and "basic regulation" (see below). If this referral is effective and the 
patient shows evidence of a minimum level of social and self-regulation, the GP will be prepared 
to provide methadone. "Basic social regulation" concerns the following points: 
<ul> 
<li>medical insurance 
<li>housing 
<li>stable income Situation through work or welfare payments 
<li>the ability to attend appointments 
<li>the ability to manage with weekly provision of methadone 
<li>minimal use of other drugs</ul> 
<p>It is important to detect not only a good period of stable addiction behavior and social 
integration but also a negative change in the clients. These occur regularly; good observation 
and registration of clients' behavior are important. Typical reasons why a GP client is referred 
back to the GG&GD are: 
<ul> 
<li>coming too early for a prescription, with vague, often creative, excuses 
<li>asking for benzodiazepines with a high abuse potential 
<li>unkempt appearance 
<li>complaints of family members and significant others 
<li>police report of selling methadone on the street 
</ul> 
<p>After a warning, such a client is sent back to the GG&GD, which has no waiting list for such 
returns. At the GG&GD, the methadone regimen is continued immediately, in a day program. 
This modus operandi entails the risk of diversion of methadone, The exact amount is unknown, 
A realistic estimate puts methadone at 10% to 15% of all prescribed, take-home dosages. It is 
consumed by drug users who have no recourse for legal methadone, such as illegal foreign 
addicts. 
<p>There are 400 GPs in Amsterdam (1,500 patients per practice),of whom half are prepared to 
serve regulated drug users sent to them by the GG&GD. A total of 1,428 methadone patients 
were -sent to GPs in 1993. Expressed in "provision days," (calendar days on which methadone is 
given to a particular patient) Amsterdam GPs assume 40% of the burden of methadone provision. 
Remarkably, they provide this service while being paid no more than the basic 180 guilders per 
year for each patient, despite the fact that these patients appear every week (Table V). 
<p> This remarkable form of GP service dates from 1981, the period in which the Amsterdam 
drug epidemic threatened to run out of control. It emerged from the following agreements, 
which ",ere made with representatives of the Amsterdam General Practitioners Association: 
<ul> 
<li>methadone provision through the GP to be on a voluntary basis 
<li>a maximum of 10 drug patients per practice 
<li>only "socially regulated" drug clients to be treated in the practice, with the difficult and 
complicated cases to be treated by the GG&GD 
<li>support from the GG&GD for the GP in the form of 'joint consultation and the promotion of 
expertise 
<li>option is kept open to send patients back to the GG&GD without a waiting list if they do not 
adhere to the program of treatment 
</ul> 
<p>It is interesting to note that these agreements contravened the then policies of the Health 
Ministry, which in the same year sent to all Dutch doctors a letter containing its own guidelines 
for methadone treatment. These guidelines would have made GP provision of methadone 
practically impossible. As a result of the Prevailing drug crisis in Amsterdam, the city more or 
less rose in revolt. The Amsterdam GPs in particular were not ready to play 
the expected part in a national policy of passive denial, and instead gave priority to the real 
medical problems of a large city.<p> 
 
<b>Results</b> 
 
<p>The voluntary commitment of Amsterdam GPs to the provision of methadone, apparently, is 
permanent. Potential weaknesses in the system include the risk of double provision and the 
possibility of some patients returning too early for their next prescription. However, in practice 
such events seem rare. From the total amount of methadone provided in Amsterdam in 1993, 
only 2.2% was found to have been given to patients twice, or too early.(2) It seems that, with a 
good-quality and accessible public health safety net of structured low-threshold methadone 
provision, the GPs can cope very well with their role in the system. 
<p>A very useful spin-off effect of GP involvement has been that the urban health-care system- 
which includes the hospitals and Polyclinics-has learned to treat drug users without being afraid 
of them. To put it another way, the fact that 80% of the HIV-positive drug users enjoy normal, 
regular, and thus very good medical care can e credited to this "normalization of use." 
<p> 
<a href="methmain.html">Methadone Main Page</a><br> 
<a href="tlcmain.html">The Lindesmith Center</a> 
<p> 
 
<b>References</b> 
<p> 
<ol> 
