<li><a name="note1"></a>The Treasury Department's antimaintenance 
position was upheld in two 
cases before the 
Supreme Court in 1919; Webb et al. v. United States and United States v. 
Doremus. Two 
subsequent cases repudiated the Webb decision (Lindner v. United States 
(1925) and Boyd v. 
United States (1926); however, the Narcotics Division of the Prohibition Unit 
of the Treasury 
Department chose to adopt the antimaintenance position as set forth in the 
Doremus and Webb 
decisions. <a href="#back1">(Back)</a> 
<li><a name="note2"></a>This section on Federal leadership was prepared 
