<html>   
<head>   
<title>Medical Maintenance: The Treatment of Chronic...(The Lindesmith Center)</title>   
</head>   
<BODY bgcolor="FFFFFF" link="0000FF" vlink="871F8" text="000000">     <center><h4>THE     
LINDESMITH CENTER</h4></center>       
<center><img align=middle src=line.gif width=600 alt=#></center><br>   
   
<center><h3>   
Medical Maintenance:<br>The Treatment of Chronic   
Opiate Dependence in General Medical Practice</h3></center>   
<p>   
<font size=2><i>Novick, David M., and Herman Joseph. "Medical Maintenance:<br>   
The Treatment of Chronic Opiate Dependence in General<br>   
Medical Practice." Journal of Substance Abuse Treatment,<br>   
8 (1991):233-239.</i></font><hr>
<center><font size=2><i>This document has been reprinted electronically by permission. All rights  
reserved.</i></font></center><hr>   
<p>   
<blockquote>   
<b>Abstract--</b> Medical maintenance was created to treat rehabilitated methadone maintenance patients   
within    
the context of general medical practice. One hundred methadone patients who met screening criteria were    
transferred for continuing care from traditional methadone clinics either to the practices of  hospital-based    
physicians or to a health maintenance organization.  Patients see their physicians about once per month,   
submit    
urine samples at the time of the office visits, drink a dose of methadone in the presence of their doctor or   
nurse, and    
receive a 28-day supply of methadone in pill or tablet form.  The methadone prescriptions are filled by the   
hospital    
pharmacies.  Physicians are responsible for the patients' annual physicals and can treat patients for other   
conditions.     
In our initial analysis of medical maintenance, 82.5 % of the patients remained in good standing and 5%   
left the    
program voluntarily in good standing; the remaining 12.5% who were unable to respond favorably were   
returned to    
clinic programs. For rehabilitated patients requiring long-term or life-long care, medical maintenance is a   
viable    
alternative to traditional clinic programs.  With proper policies and procedures, medical maintenance can   
be    
implemented in many hospitals.</blockquote>   
<p>   
   
<b>INTRODUCTION</b>   
<p>   
   
<font size=2>   
The views and procedures outlined in this paper do not reflect the policies of the New York State Division   
of    
Substance Abuse Services.<br>   
This work was supported in part by National  Institute on Drug Abuse Treatment Center grant number   
IP50-   
DA0513-01 and a grant from the Herbert and Nell Singer Philanthropic Fund of the Jewish Communal   
Fund.<br>   
Correspondence and Requests for reprints should be addressed to Herman Joseph, Bureau of Research and    
Evaluation, New York  State Division of  Substance Abuse Services, 55 West 125th Street, New York City,   
NY    
10027.</font>   
   
<p>   
   
Over the past twenty-five years, methadone maintenance treatment  has evolved from a small research   
project to the    
largest treatment method for chronic opiate dependence in the United States (Dole & Nyswander, 1965;   
Dole,    
Nyswander, & Kreek, 1966; Cooper, Altman, Brown, & Czechowicz, 1983; Cooper, 1989; Zweben &   
Payte, 1990).     
Methadone programs are operated from specially licensed clinics that are usually affiliated with hospitals   
or    
community social service agencies but are sometimes privately owned.  All programs in the United States   
are    
subject to federal, state, and local regulations that delineate the amount of methadone prescribed to   
patients, the    
frequency of clinic visits, the ratio of patients to counseling staff, and the provision of medical and   
supportive    
services.  These regulations were designed to insure uniform standards of delivery of service by the staff   
and to curb    
possible abuses by marginal patients who may divert the medication and present numerous social,   
behavioral, and    
medical problems to the program.   
<p>However, there exists a group of patients who have achieved a high level of social and    
personal adjustment and therefore do not require ongoing counseling.  Furthermore, the    
regulations of clinics that were implemented to curb abuses of marginal patients may impede the    
further progress and adjustment of rehabilitated patients.  This paper describes a program--   
medical maintenance--that was designed to remove rehabilitated methadone patients from    
traditional clinics and to treat them within the context of general medical practice (i.e., private    
office practices and health maintenance organizations) (Novick et al., 198 b).  It is our hope that    
by providing a detailed description of the policies and procedures of medical maintenance, we will    
facilitate the development of similar programs at other institutions.<p>   
   
<b>WHY MEDICAL MAINTENANCE</b><p>   
   
Extensively regulated methadone clinics may be necessary for treating large numbers of patients    
who require medical, social, and rehabilitative services.  However, not all methadone patients    
need the structure imposed by extensive governmental regulations nor the services offered in the    
clinics.  Some patients are employed, married, integrated into the mainstream of society, and    
psychologically stable.  Such rehabilitated patients have severed their ties with the street drug    
culture, and their abuse of illicit drugs or alcohol is minimal or nonexistent.   
<p>Traditional clinical services, policies, and regulations are usually targeted to the needs of    
marginal patients with employment, poly-drug abuse, housing, and behavioral and medical    
problems, including infection with the human immunodeficiency virus (HIV).  These policies may    
hamper the personal, social, and business advancement of rehabilitated patients.  For example, the    
least restrictive schedule of clinic visits allowable under federal regulations in a methadone clinic    
is once per week.  In many instances program policy or state regulations mandate even more    
frequent visits for 11 patients; some states do not permit take-home doses, and patients must    
report daily.  Therefore, methadone pickup schedules in traditional clinics can limit travel for    
business or vacations.  Also, if patients take extended trips, their confidentiality may be    
compromised.  They will be required to obtain methadone from designated clinics in the localities    
of their destinations and to conform to the regulations of these clinics.   
   
<P>However, the patient's confidentiality is already compromised merely by attending a licensed    
methadone clinic and being identified by other patients and persons in the neighborhood of the    
clinic who may observe the patient entering and leaving the facility.  Also, rehabilitated patients    
may feel that the program's services, procedures, and policies are irrelevant for their needs,    
restrictive, and somewhat stigmatizing (Des Jarlais, Joseph, Dole, & Nyswander, 1985; Dole &    
Nyswander, 1976).   
<p>Medical maintenance was created primarily to address these issues by treating socially    
rehabilitated methadone patients within the context of general medical practice as an alternative to    
the formal clinic setting.  In this respect medical maintenance for the treatment of opiate addiction    
is similar to maintenance therapy in general medical practice for other chronic illnesses such as    
the prescribing by a physician of insulin for diabetics and carbemazapine for epileptics (Dole,    
1971; Newman, 1987).   
<p>Although the primary purpose of  medical maintenance is to provide more appropriate    
medical care for qualified individuals, this program also provides benefits to the general    
community.  When patients are transferred to medical maintenance from clinic programs, spaces    
in these programs become available for new heroin addicts.  Enrolling as many heroin addicts as    
possible in treatment programs is particularly important in the ongoing epidemic of HIV infection    
(Novick et al., 1990).  Finally, a11 of society benefits when enhanced services are available and    
when citizens can function at their highest capabilities.  Medical maintenance facilitates these    
goals.   
   
<p>   
<b>PHASES OF METHADONE TREATMENT</B>    
<p>   
Methadone maintenance treatment may be subdivided into four phases, the first three phases of    
which take place within traditional methadone clinics.  Phase 1 is the stabilization period, which    
lasts for about 3 months.  During this period the patient is stabilized on an appropriate dose of    
methadone and develops the necessary tolerance to methadoneís narcotic and analgesic properties    
to function normally with unimpaired affect and responses.     
<p>Phase 2 may be indefinite.  During this period patients are assessed concerning their ongoing    
needs, and plans are made for relevant services and employment.  Some patients may have serious    
personal, social, and medical problems, including HIV infection, and may be unable to advance    
beyond a certain level of functioning.  Others may take advantage of rehabilitation, vocational and    
educational opportunities and achieve  a high level of functioning.  Patients during this phase    
report from one to seven times per week depending on their adjustment and duration of time in    
treatment.  They receive counseling, are referred to agencies for further help if indicated, submit    
urine samples at least eight times per year, and drink their methadone dose before a nurse when    
they report.   
<p>phase 3, known as After Care, is available on a very limited basis under exemptions from    
Federal Regulations (Barthwell, Senay, Marks, & White, 1989; Novick et al., 1989a).  Patients    
who have made successful adjustments in phase 2 report once every 2 weeks, drink a prescribed    
dose of methadone under the observation of a nurse, submit a urine test, and receive a 2 -weekís    
supply of take-home methadone in liquid form.  There is little counseling in phase 3, since the    
patients referred are usually employed, socially productive, and without a history of serious    
secondary drug or alcohol abuse.  After a period of about 6 months, the patients in phase 3 can    
apply for admission to phase 4 or medical maintenance.  However, successful patients In phase 2,    
if they wish to and are considered by the staff to be stable and trustworthy, may also be considered    
for admission to medical maintenance.  Therefore, while phases 1 and 2 of methadone    
maintenance treatment are considered a right for heroin addicts, after-care and medical    
maintenance are considered privileges for successful methadone patients.   
   
<p>   
<b>DESCRIPTION OF THE MEDICAL<br>   
MAINTENANCE PROGRAM</b>   
<p>   
The current medical maintenance program was started with 1-5 methadone patients by Dr. Marie E.   
Nyswander at    
The Rockefeller University in June of 1983.  Upon Dr. Nyswander's retirement in 1985, the patients were    
transferred to the care of hospital-based physicians at Beth Israel Medical Center or into the Family Care   
Group    
Practice, a health maintenance organization affiliated with the St. Lukeís-Roosevelt Hospital Medical   
Center in New    
York City.  The latter caters to families with medical plans and offers comprehensive medical care in a   
commodious    
setting that resembles a private physician's office.   
<p>In medical maintenance, methadone patients are integrated into general medical practice with patients   
treated    
for conditions other than chronic opiate addiction.  The patients are treated by physicians in their hospital-  
based    
offices or in the Family Care Group Practice office located in an apartment building adjacent to St. Lukeís-   
Roosevelt Medical Center.  Patients enrolled in medical maintenance make monthly appointments to see   
their    
physicians and pay a fee for the visit.  In addition to prescribing methadone, the physicians can also treat   
methadone    
patients for a variety of acute and chronic medical conditions.  A physical examination is performed   
annually.   
<p>At the discretion of the doctor, patients can report approximately once per month and receive a 28-day   
supply of    
medication.  If problems such as loss or misuse of medication, substance abuse, or social instability should   
arise, the    
physician may require the patient to report more frequently.  Therefore, with the flexibility of a more   
liberal    
reporting and prescribing schedule, physicians are able to make decisions about the patient's ongoing care   
based on    
the individual's needs rather than on imposed regulations.   
<p>The physicians' prescriptions for methadone are filled by the hospital pharmacy, delivered to the   
physician's    
office and stored in a narcotics cabinet within 24 hours of the patient's visit.  Methadone is prescribed in a   
solid    
form (diskettes or tablets).  At the time of the office visit, the patient drinks a prescribed dose of methadone   
under    
observation of the physician or nurse to demonstrate continued tolerance to the dose of methadone, submits   
a urine    
sample, and receives a take-home supply of methadone.  The patient may also discuss with the physician or   
other    
medical staff problems that arose within the past month.   
<p>The urine is tested by a private laboratory for opiates, methadone, cocaine, amphetamines, and   
barbiturates.     
Testing for additional substances can be completed at the request of the doctor.  Neither witnessed urine   
collections    
nor random urine testing are performed routinely, but the physician reserves the right to utilize either or   
both of    
these methods.  A monthly fee of $60.00 is charged for the office visit; this includes the cost of the   
methadone and    
drug screening.  Theoretically, patients can be reimbursed through their third-party insurance.  However,   
almost all    
refuse to file insurance claims because of confidentiality issues unless a medical diagnosis other than   
chronic opiate    
dependence can be made.  They are concerned that through the insurance claims employers may learn   
about their    
past addiction histories and current treatment, possibly jeopardizing their employment.   
   
<p>   
<b>CRITERIA FOR ADMISSION<br>   
TO THE PROGRAM</b>   
<p>   
   
The following criteria have been developed for admission to medical maintenance.
<p>
<ol>  
<li>A minimum of 5 years of methadone maintenance treatment.  If possible, applicants should have   
been    
enrolled for at    
	least 6 months in after care.   
<li>Stable employment and/or productive activity such as homemaking or enrollment in school or   
college    
within the past    
	3 years.   
   
<li>A verifiable means of financial support.   
   
<li>No involvement in criminal behavior within the past 3 years.   
   
<li>No illegal drug use or excessive alcohol use within the past 3 years.   
   
<li>The patient should be emotionally stable as assessed by review of clinical records, a personal   
interview,    
and, if    
	necessary, communication with the staff of the referring clinic.   
   
<li>No ties to street activities or illicit drug users, which might promote diversion or relapse.   
   
<li>A positive record in methadone treatment.  Patients shall have attended clinic as directed, been   
responsible    
with take-   
	home medications by not losing or diverting medication, submitted urines for testing, and not   
presented    
behavior    
	problems in clinic.   
   
<li>A recommendation for medical maintenance by clinic staff.   
   
<li>Patients and referring clinic are of the opinion that long-term methadone maintenance is necessary   
to    
consolidate and    
	improve the quality of their lives.   
   
<li>Patients under care of other physicians who prescribe medication for an emotional or serious   
chronic    
medical 	condition would be considered eligible for medical maintenance if the patient permits an ongoing    
interchange of 	information between the doctors.   
<li>Patient enters the program voluntarily.  
</ol> 
<p>   
Patients are also informed that if they wish to discontinue medical maintenance or if the physician   
determines over a    
period of time that medical maintenance is inappropriate, they can return to their previous clinics.  Patients   
are also    
advised that medical maintenance is a research project under an Investigational New Drug permit from the   
Food and    
Drug Administration, and that they may be asked to volunteer for additional studies (Novick et al., 1989,   
1990).     
Although our program is located in New York City, patients from other cities and states are eligible for    
consideration for admission as long as they can travel to New York City for visits and can maintain   
effective    
communication with their medical maintenance physician.<p>   
   
<b>ADMISSIONS, REJECTIONS, AND REFUSALS</b>   
<p>   
   
It is important to examine the reasons for accepting or rejecting applicants for medical maintenance, and   
the reasons    
patients give for refusing to enter the program although accepted.  These factors define meaningful   
limitations of the    
program.  Since the inception of medical maintenance, 122 methadone patients applied for admission.    
They were    
interviewed and their medical records were reviewed by the administrative physician of the medical   
maintenance    
program.  The intake interviews cover the applicant's addiction, treatment, and legal history; current and   
past health    
problems, educational level, employment or means of support, living arrangements, and assessments of   
social and    
psychological adjustment.  One hundred methadone patients were accepted into the program because they   
met the    
above admission criteria, 16 were rejected, and 6 declined to enter although they were accepted for   
admission.   
<p>Of the 16 who were rejected, 10 had episodes of drug or alcohol abuse within the 3-year period prior to   
their    
application to the program.  Cocaine use predominated followed by excessive drinking, use of nonopiate   
drugs and    
heroin.  Six patients were rejected for other reasons: three had not complied with clinic regulations, one   
was    
rearrested within the past 3 years, one patient was emotionally unstable, and another had a spouse in a   
methadone    
program who was using cocaine.  When an applicant for medical maintenance has a spouse in methadone    
maintenance treatment, we have insisted on interviewing the spouse and obtaining information from the   
spouse's    
clinic.  It is important that the spouse is also doing well in treatment as the emotional stability of the   
applicant for    
medical maintenance may be affected by a spouse with serious problems.  Also, a spouse who is not doing   
well may    
have access to and abuse the methadone dispensed in medical maintenance.  Of the six patients who   
withdrew their    
applications for admission, two found the program's hours inconvenient, one decided to remain in his   
originating    
clinic, one patient refused to cooperate with the intake process, another moved, and the sixth declined to   
enter    
without giving a specific reason.   
<p>Our initial outcome data have been reported previously (Novick et al., 1988a), 1988b), and a long-term   
analysis    
is in progress.  Among the first 40 patients (Novick et al., 1988b), 33 (82.5%) remained in treatment for 12   
to 55    
months.  Five patients had to return to conventional methadone clinics because of cocaine abuse, one   
detoxified, and    
one voluntarily returned to the clinic.   
<p>   
<b>BENEFITS FOR THE PATIENT<br>   
AND THE PHYSICIAN</b>   
<p>   
   
The patients perceive many advantages of medical maintenance over treatment in a traditional methadone   
clinic.     
For example, patients are able to travel freely for extended periods of time.  Also, their confidentiality is   
more    
closely safeguarded, as their condition is treated within the context of a general medical practice where   
patients with    
a variety of conditions are treated.  Therefore, they will not be seen entering or leaving a designated clinic   
where    
only methadone treatment is administered, and will avoid being identified as a methadone patient by   
neighborhood    
residents or other methadone patients.  Thus, they are further removed from the drug subculture.  Medical    
maintenance patients are treated by a private physician with whom they can develop an ongoing trustful    
relationship.  Their general medical needs other than methadone can be addressed by a knowledgeable   
practitioner.   
<p>Most patients in medical maintenance are on 28-day reporting schedules that enable them to take   
extended    
vacations and business trips.  Since methadone is prescribed in tablet form, patients are able to store the   
medication    
more efficiently than liquid methadone dispensed in bottles for daily use and requiring refrigeration.  Many   
patients    
have perceived liquid methadone as a confidentiality risk because it could be found in the refrigerator by   
friends or    
relatives including children who did not know the patient was on methadone.   
<p>Medical maintenance enables physicians to treat the condition of chronic opiate dependence within   
private    
medical practice in an open, responsible manner for the first time since the passage of the Harrison Act in   
1914    
(subsequently mentioned in this article).  Doctors can experience for themselves that success can be   
achieved among    
a group of patients previously considered intractable and outside the purview of general medical practice.     
Therefore, the dimensions of their private practice and experience are expanded.  The physicians in the   
pilot study    
have found that the personalities of the majority of the medical maintenance patients fall within the range   
of chronic    
medical patients found in private medical practice.   
<p>   
<b>SPECIAL CONSIDERATIONS</b>   
<p>   
During the course of medical maintenance, situations and problems arose which required decisions   
affecting the    
policy and practices of the program.  Life situations of patients changed, and the current cocaine/crack   
epidemic    
affected a small proportion of the patients.  In this section we will discuss matters that required special   
attention and    
their resolution.   
<p>Most patients in medical maintenance accept methadone treatment as a lifelong process.  Previous   
attempts at    
detoxification either were not completed or, if completed, the patients subsequently reentered treatment   
because of    
the protracted abstinence syndrome or relapse to drug use.   
<p>During medical maintenance a few patients in the program (less than 5%) asked to be detoxified.    
Since the    
primary philosophy of the program is long-term, possibly lifelong maintenance, participating physicians do   
not    
initiate detoxification.  Their approach to detoxification is therefore one of caution, yet being supportive of   
the    
patient's request.  The physician and patient discuss the medical procedure, the rate of dose reduction and   
possible    
problems such as discomfort, insomnia, return of craving, and the possibility of relapse to use of illicit   
drugs    
(Anglin, Speckart, Booth, & Ryan, 1989; Cooper et al., 1983; Dole & Joseph, 978).  The patient's medical   
history,    
emotional state, and social adjustment are factors that are considered before the procedure is initiated and   
during the    
process of detoxifying.  The process of detoxification entails a reduction of dose, usually by 10 mg, either   
every    
month or every 2 months until the patient reaches 40 mg.  At this level, the patient's dose is reduced by 5   
mg every    
one or two months until the process is completed.  However, if the patient should experience undue   
discomfort or    
craving that can precipitate relapse and jeopardize social, personal, and psychological gains made in   
treatment, the    
procedure is stopped, and the patient is restablized.   
<p>Another issue relates to changes in the patient's methadone dose during maintenance.  Although   
patients were    
successfully maintained for years on stabilized doses of methadone, some did request dose changes.    
Usually the    
request is for an increase since the doses in many clinics tend to be low.  Therefore, some of the patients   
may    
experience withdrawal symptoms within a 24-hour period.  The symptoms are discussed with the physician   
and, if    
indicated, the patient's dose is adjusted to a level at which symptoms are eliminated.  In medical   
maintenance, the    
median dose of methadone has been 60 mg daily (Novick et al., 1990).   
<p>Responsibility in caring for a 28-day supply of medicine is an important obligation for patients to   
assume.     
Therefore, most patients are not immediately placed on a monthly reporting schedule unless they were in   
an after-   
care program where they reported every 2 weeks for at least 6 months and demonstrated that they were   
able to take    
the medication as directed without incidents or losses.  Patients entering medical maintenance from a   
program    
where they report weekly are placed on a twice per month reporting schedule for a period of at least 2   
months.  The    
patient's adjustment is evaluated by the physician before a monthly schedule is considered.  Loss of   
medication in    
medical maintenance is a serious violation.  If patients misplace or lose their take-home medication more   
than once,    
they are returned to the clinic program.   
<p>Addiction is a chronic relapsing condition (Dole, 1988).  Although methadone maintenance is    
pharmacologically effective for attenuating and stopping the use of heroin, the medication has no direct    
pharmacological effect on alcohol or nonopiate drugs Unfortunately, the cocaine/crack epidemic has had a    
significant impact on a minority of the patients.  If the cocaine problem appears severe, immediate transfer   
to a    
conventional methadone clinic is warranted.  For sporadic cocaine use, the physician's judgment may be   
that the    
problem could be overcome by counseling by the physician, referrals for further counseling, and increased   
reporting    
with frequent urine testing.  If there are no improvements in a period of about two months, patients should   
be    
returned to their methadone clinics for continued treatment.   
<p>Patients entering medical maintenance are in a socially stable situation.  However, this may change   
over time    
since patients can lose their jobs, decide to separate from or divorce their spouses, become seriously ill, or   
become    
despondent as a result of serious illness or death of a close family member or friend.  These situations may   
lead to    
behavior that may include drug or alcohol abuse, psychological depression, and financial instability.  The   
physician    
can refer the patient for assistance and counseling in these matters and see the patients more often until the    
emergency situation is resolved.  When a patient becomes unemployed, a more frequent schedule of visits   
is often    
warranted because of the greater risk of emotional, financial, and social problems.  In one case after the   
illness and    
death of a parent, a patient developed a temporary episode of alcoholism.  However, the patient was   
successfully    
treated and is now continuing in medical maintenance.  Should the situation become untenable, the patient   
can be    
referred back to the clinic where there is a greater degree of structure and counseling.   
<p>   
<b>CONSIDERATIONS FOR EXPANSION</b>   
<p>   
A final consideration is the potential to expand medical maintenance to include all eligible patients.  The   
number of    
such patients nationwide is unknown.  However, at the Beth Israel Medical Center in New York City over   
8,000    
patients are in methadone maintenance treatment.  Of this number it is speculated by the authors that   
perhaps 7%    
would both be eligible and want to enter the program.  If all eligible patients nationwide were enrolled in   
medical    
maintenance, the public health benefit of improved control of HIV infection in heroin addicts would likely   
ensue as    
thousands of such patients could enter treatment to replace those transferred to medical maintenance.   
<p>Limiting factors for such an expansion of Medical Maintenance include difficulties in recruiting   
physicians to    
accept medical maintenance patients in their private practices, reluctance of some clinics to part with their   
most    
successful patients, reluctance of some patients to leave their familiar clinic setting, reluctance of some   
hospital    
staffs and administrators to support substance abuse programs within the hospitals, and reluctance of   
pharmacies    
both inside and outside of hospitals to dispense methadone.  To make medical maintenance a national   
program,    
these problems will have to be addressed.   
<p>   
<b>RECRUITING PHYSICIANS</b>   
<p>   
The recruitment of capable and interested physicians is both pivotal and essential if the medical   
maintenance    
program is to succeed and expand.  The physicians affiliated with the medical maintenance program have   
been    
trained in internal medicine or family practice.  Many of the patients have transferred their primary medical   
care to    
their doctors in the program and are now being treated by their medical maintenance physicians for acute   
and    
chronic conditions in addition to opiate dependence.   
<p>Past experience in the treatment of drug abuse is not necessary.  Only two of the six participating   
physicians in    
the Beth Israel program and the medical director of the St. Luke's-Roosevelt Hospital Family Care Group   
Practice    
had experience treating methadone patients in the clinic programs.  Sometimes physicians who work in   
methadone    
clinics may harbor biased attitudes since they have been exposed to patients with serious medical, social,   
and    
behavioral problems.  Competence, compassion, and a positive attitude toward substance abuse treatment   
are    
important attributes of medical maintenance physicians.  Physicians recruited into medical maintenance are   
trained    
about methadone, medical safety of the drug (Kreek, 1973), stabilization, and the procedures and policies   
that have    
been developed over the past 6 years.   
<p>   
<b>THE HARRISON ACT AND<br>   
MEDICAL MAINTENANCE</b>   
<p>   
In 1914 the Harrison Act was passed by Congress.  Physicians and pharmacists who prescribed and   
distributed    
narcotics were required to pay a tax and keep records of all such transactions, which would be open to   
inspection by    
the Treasury Department.  The law was narrowly interpreted to prevent physicians from prescribing   
narcotics to    
maintain addicts.  In two cases -in March of 1919, the Supreme Court upheld an anti-maintenance position   
(Webb et    
al. v. United States, United States v. Doremus).  Both physicians were accused of gross over-prescribing.    
However,    
the anti-maintenance position was reversed in two subsequent cases -- Lindner v. United States (1925) and   
Boyd v.    
United States (1926).  In these cases, the court distinguished between doctors who prescribed narcotics to   
addicts in    
"good faith" to relieve the suffering associated with addiction and those who prescribed to "enable   
recipients to    
indulge their acquired longing for the drug and its effects" (Gewirtz, 1969) The Bureau of Narcotics of the   
Treasury    
Department chose instead to adopt an anti-maintenance interpretation of the Harrison Act as set forth in the   
Webb    
decision.  Subsequently, physicians who prescribed narcotics to addicts were harassed and prosecuted.    
Opiate    
maintenance clinics that operated after the enactment of the Harrison Act were closed by 1923   
(Courtwright,    
Joseph, & Des Jarlais 1989).   
<p>Until the establishment of methadone maintenance treatment in 1965, addicts had to rely mainly on a   
criminal    
and sometimes violent black market to obtain drugs.  Medical maintenance, however, returns the treatment   
of the    
opiate-dependent patient to an integrated general medical practice rather than to the segregated licensed   
clinic    
system.  The program, although currently considered a research project by the Food and Drug   
Administration,    
conforms to the philosophy espoused by the Supreme Court in the Lindner and Boyd cases.  Methadone is    
prescribed in good faith by private physicians to relieve the ill effects of addiction.   
<p>   
<b>CONCLUSIONS</b>   
<p>   
Medical Maintenance has been developed and evaluated over the past 6 years.  It has shown itself to be a   
successful    
method for treating a selected group of socially rehabilitated methadone patients in the private medical   
practices of    
physicians affiliated with medical centers and health maintenance organizations.  The doctors were   
recruited and    
trained by the administrative physician of the program.   
<p>However, screening and intake procedures do not guarantee success.  Stressful life situations that can   
arise    
during the course of treatment (e.g., onset of the cocaine/crack epidemic, loss of a job, death or serious   
illness of a    
loved one, dissolution of a marriage, onset of a chronic medical condition, or serious acute illness) may   
adversely    
affect the patient's adjustment.  This can lead to abuse of the methadone medication, illicit drug abuse,   
depression,    
or irresponsible behavior.  The physician can increase the reporting schedule, offer counseling, refer the   
patient to    
medical or social agencies for additional help, or, if indicated, refer the patient back to the traditional   
methadone    
clinic for continued treatment.  Patients who enter medical maintenance should be made aware of the   
limitations of    
the services that are available and must understand that failure to adjust in medical maintenance does not   
mean    
failure in methadone treatment.   
<p>The program is tailored to a select group of patients who are able to function without the formal   
structure and    
regulations of a traditional clinic. Most have enhanced their lives through medical maintenance.  They have    
continued working, and some have received promotions; those in business have increased their earnings.    
They have    
been able to travel for extended periods of time without the constraints of weekly or biweekly reporting.    
The    
program has enhanced their self-worth by removing them from a potentially stigmatizing situation in   
clinics that are    
currently overwhelmed with the problems of the inner city -- homelessness, HIV infection, unemployment,   
and    
cocaine/crack abuse.  The physicians have also benefited, since they are seeing success in a group of   
patients that    
were previously rejected by private practitioners because of legal restrictions and inadequate medical   
interventions.     
While methadone maintenance has transformed the treatment of chronic opiate dependence for thousands   
of    
intractable addicts, medical maintenance has enabled a select group of successful methadone patients to be   
treated    
as medical patients integrated into a general medical practice.<p>   
<a href="methmain.html">Methadone Main Page</a>   
<a href="tlcmain.html">The Lindesmith Center</a><p>   
   
   
