<html> 
<head> 
<title> John Watters : A Hero </title> 
</head> 
<body bgcolor="FFFFFF" link="006699" vlink="339999" text="000000">
<center><h4>THE 
LINDESMITH CENTER</h4></center> 
<center><img align=middle src=line.gif width=600 alt=#></center><br> 
 
<center><h2> John Watters : A Hero of Harm Reduction 
</h2></center><p> 
<center><h4><blockquote><i>"Only with burning patience shall we conquer the<br> 
 splendid city that will give light, justice, and dignity<br> 
		 to all men."<br>--Pablo Neruda</i></blockquote></h4></center> 
<p> 
<font size=3><center>By Ernest Drucker<br> 
Montefiore Medical Center/<br> 
Albert Einstein College of Medicine<br> 
Bronx, New York 10467</center></font> 
<p> 
<font size=2><i>Drucker, Ernest. " John Watters : A Hero of Harm<br> 
Reduction." Adapted from an article to appear in the<br>
<b>International Journal of Drug Policy</b> 7(1):1996.</i></font size><hr> 
 
<p> 
 
 
 
John Watters was a hero of harm reduction. He had a warrior's determination to get at the truth through 
science. His work was always remarkable for its rigor, creativity, and elegance. John's research helped 
unmask AIDS' secrets and captured some of the most elusive yet most important epidemiological realities 
of the drug world. He advocated passionately for a humane and intelligent drug policy: What was the point 
of good science if it wasn't translated into action? John Watters did it all. 
<p> 
I last saw John in March of 1995, at the Harm Reduction Conference in Florence. He was just coming off a 
bad flu, suffering jet lag after a flight from San Francisco, and rushing away to get some slides for his talk. 
Unfortunately, I had a competing commitment and missed what was, by all accounts, a superb presentation. 
John blew out of town as quickly as he had come in; ponytail trailing behind as he ran through the narrow 
streets, dodging the Italian rush hour traffic. 
<p> 
That's the way John and I normally saw each other; at AIDS meetings and drug research or public health 
conferences, hanging out in hotel lobbies and noisy dinners with too many people for a serious 
conversation. Although we watched baseball and drank beer at my apartment in New York one summer, 
we usually had a country between us. But I loved his attitude and admired his work. 
<p> 
At the end of October I returned from a month on the road to find an email from John: a story which he 
labeled "Greed vs. Internet." The story was about the father of a young child (as John was) who 
unknowingly agrees to pay for a vastly overpriced cookie recipe while eating at a fancy restaurant. The 
man retaliates by distributing the recipe freely through the Internet. The tale is old and apocryphal; the 
decision to disseminate it is classic John: a bit of moral jui jitsu, which I immediately forwarded it to a 
bunch of other folks. 
<p> 
On November 23, 1995, I received another email from San Francisco. This one was tagged "Some 
Unfortunate News." It carried word of John's death at age 46 from a "suspected heart attack." A few days 
later, I heard reports that the cause of death was probably a drug overdose. Obituaries appeared in the New 
York Times, the Washington Post, and the International Herald Tribune. Some mentioned the probable 
cause as drugs, but all emphasized John's important achievements in AIDS and addiction research, and in 
public health. 
<p> 
On hearing of John's death, I felt the predictable shock and disbelief. In the initial uncertainty about the 
exact events surrounding his death, some tried to deny the harsh reality of his death from drugs. One of 
John's colleagues at Stanford, "outraged by the lurid headline and sensationalist...spin" of an article 
published in the San Francisco Chronicle, rejected this truth about her friend and teacher. For her "Dr. 
Watters was simply not a drug user." She went on to criticize the paper for its "inability to resist the 
temptation of libelous irony" by linking John 's 
professional life to the means of his death. 
<p> 
A few months after John died, the drug reform community was hit again with the death of a vital syringe 
exchange activist, Brian Weil at age 41. With the volunteers of Citywide Needle Exchange, Brian went to 
SROs and shooting galleries to reach populations missed by other syringe exchanges. Brian also died of an 
overdose. 
<p> 
Both John and Brian contributed significantly to the theory and practice of harm reduction. In the 1980s in 
northern California, John had quickly understood the need to establish harm reduction policies and 
practices in the U.S. Today the rate of infection among California's 200,000 drug injectors is less than one 
fifth that of New York or Washington, D.C. Brian worked as effectively with IDUs as he did with 
government officials in Albany. He was trying to convince those officials to grant an exemption to New 
York's paraphernalia and prescription laws so that his syringe exchange could operate legally and get 
financial support. 
<p> 
The harm reduction movement, which these men helped create and sustain, has saved thousands of lives. 
So, many of us find ourselves asking, why couldn't John's and Brian's have been among them? 
<p> 
The deaths of John and Brian remind us of the hazards of heroin--a powerful drug whose actions are still 
not fully understood and can be highly unpredictable, especially in combination with alcohol or other 
drugs. The risks of heroin use are exacerbated by prohibition, which creates a need for clandestine 
acquisition and use. In these circumstances, even an experienced and sophisticated user never really knows 
what he or she is getting. The Drug Enforcement Administration (DEA) reports huge variations in the 
potency of street heroin in the U.S. Even within the same city, the potency of a $10 bag of dope bought 
from the same dealer on two successive days can vary by 100%. This is enough of a difference to kill the 
occasional, nontolerant user, which (judging from their active and productive lives) both John and Brian 
probably were. 
<p> 
American culture has always lionized the former addict; the culture defers to his/her seeming wisdom on 
addiction and its "cure." But it completely denies the legitimacy of current users, steadfastly refusing to see 
them as anything but demonized stereotypes, regardless of professional or political productivity. Yet it is 
the personal experience and commitment of this broad group of drug users that has been a most potent (and 
dangerous) credential of the growing harm reduction movement. 
<p> 
The continued use of illicit drugs by individuals who are deeply committed to minimizing the potential for 
harm of these same drugs may at first appear to be a contradiction. But around the world, active drug users 
(often living with HIV/AIDS) have, since the start of the epidemic, been the key to many effective AIDS 
prevention efforts. In the Netherlands, Great Britain, and Australia, current users of illicit drugs sit at the 
same table with academic and government public health professionals. Their organizations, unions, and 
user groups are funded to educate and assist other active users in preventing the spread of AIDS and 
assisting drug users in getting help when they need it. The data are now quite clear that this approach 
works to reduce risk, and provides better access to a range of helping services, including drug treatment. 
<p> 
Those in the field of AIDS prevention now understand that current users play a pivotal role in reaching 
those at greatest risk, and can be a potent force in reducing that risk. America's community-based needle 
exchanges were created and operated by a partnership of professionals with active and former drug users 
and abusers. The commitment and hard work of those people has established a network which now reach 
over 200,000 drug users in scores of American cities. All this progress was made without support from the 
government public health agencies, which have had to be dragged kicking and screaming to acknowledge 
the value of NEPs. But the story of the work, commitment, and impact of drug users and abusers is seldom 
told in public. 
<p> 
Perhaps because of the dominant culture of silence, those in the drug policy reform movement also fall 
silent if someone of John's stature is characterized as a user of "hard" drugs. Is our silence shame? Do we 
accept the repressive and judgmental assumptions of drug prohibition and forget that the use of mind- 
altering substances (for better or for worse) is an almost universal constant in the human condition? The 
heart of the problem facing harm reduction in the U.S. is this country's steadfast refusal to acknowledge 
that drug use is as American as apple pie. So the active user, living in a system that denies this reality, must 
stay hidden in the closet -- with all its corrosive secrecy, darkness, and danger. 
<p> 
 "Be fair, be honest, and give them hell" John once prompted Alex Wodak before a presentation on 
needle exchanges to hostile U.S. health officials. Johns Watters' life reminds us how much people who use 
drugs can do in this world. His death leaves a great void and shows us just how far we still have to go. For 
me, John's life will be remembered for his "burning patience," his determination and huge commitment to 
get it right--which is how we change the world. "John threw off a lot of heat and a lot of light" Susan 
Coyle, a friend at NIDA said. "The world will be a little colder and darker without him." Amen. 
<p>
<hr> 
<p> 
<center>
<a href="http://www.lindesmith.org/tlcintro.html"><img src=subbar.jpg alt="subject index"></a><a href="http://www.lindesmith.org/tlcmain.html"><img src=hombar.jpg alt="tlc home"></a><a href="http://www.lindesmith.org/tlchot.html"><img src=hotbar.jpg alt="what's hot!"</a><br><a href="http://www.soros.org/Architext/AT-The_Lindesmith_Centerquery.html"><img src=seabar.jpg alt="search tlc"></a><a href="http://www.lindesmith.org/focal.html"><img src=focbar.jpg alt="focal point"></a><a href="http://www.lindesmith.org/tlcartic.html"><img src=libbar.jpg alt="tlc library"></a></center><p> 
