<html> 
<head> 
<title>Injection Drug Users: Tips on ManagementÖ(The Lindesmith Center)</title> 
</head> 
<body bgcolor="FFFFFF" link="006699" vlink="339999" text="000000"> 
<center><h4>THE LINDESMITH CENTER</h4></center> 
<center><img align=middle src=line.gif width=600 alt=#></center> 
<p> 
<center><h2> 
Injection Drug Users: Tips on Management<br> 
(What about Prevention?)</h2></center> 
<p> 
<font size=2><i> 
By <a href="mailto:fzflynn2@peseta.ucdavis.edu">Dr. Neil Flynn</a>, M.D., M.P.H. "Injection Drug 
Users:<br> Tips on Management (What about Prevention?)"<br> 
Presented at the North American Syringe Exchange<br> 
Conference, Milwaukee, WI. April 25-27, 1996. 
</i></font> 
<hr> 
<center><i>Reprinted with permission. All rights reserved.</i></center> 
<hr> 
<p> 
<b>Introduction</b> 
<p> 
Have you ever encountered a problem in providing care for an injection drug user (an IDU)? 
Has 
an IDU ever encountered a problem receiving care from you? In my opinion you can't ask one 
question without asking the other. That's what this discussion is about primarily--looking at the 
problems of providing medical care for drug users from different perspectives, "ours" and 
"theirs", i.e., changing the frame of reference we are used to and examining the result. 
<p> 
<b> 
Re-examining our attitudes (we "health-care providers") toward drug users</b> 
<p> 
Some common myths about "drug users" (sometimes applied to alcoholics also): 
<ul> 
<li>They are stupid. 
<li>They are all the same. 
<li>They want <b>us</b> to clean up the mess <b>they've</b> made by using drugs. 
<li><b>Drug use</b> is the cause of their illness. They brought this on themselves by using 
drugs. 
<li>They don't care about themselves, so why should we care about them? 
<li>They are hostile and demanding and unpleasant to work with. 
<li>They won't do what you tell them to do. 
<li>All they are interested in is their drugs anyway. They <i>even shoot up on my ward!</i> 
<li>They are without principles. You can't trust them. Every time I trust them I get screwed. 
<li>They lie, even when the truth would "serve them better." 
<li>They have no sense of responsibility. 
<li>They are lazy, they don't work. 
</ul> 
<p> 
How do these and other myths affect the provider-patient "relationship?" 
<p> 
Ask yourself whether the illness you are treating is <b>a direct result of the drug itself and its 
use,</b> or whether it is <b>the result of the social context in which the drug is used.</b> 
<p> 
<b>Try an experiment (not just once, but 5-10 times) and examine the results. The 
experiment:</b> 
<p> 
Make it clear to the DU patient that you are aware of his/her overall plight (both the current 
illness, and the context within which (s)he uses drugs), by directly stating so at the beginning of 
your first interview with the patient, and soliciting her/his feelings surrounding the drug use and 
the illness. 
<p> 
Make it clear that you will do your best to make them comfortable while in the hospital, even if 
that means providing them with a reasonable substitute for their street drug of choice if one is 
available. 
<p> 
Make the patient as comfortable as possible. If their drug of choice is heroin, estimate the 
amount of methadone needed to prevent withdrawal and give it within a few hours of admission. 
Adjust the second dose upward or downward based on the patient's response: somnolence, adjust 
downward; lots of complaints and agitation, adjust upward. Use a bid or q 12 hour dosing for 
methadone (10, 20, 30 or 40 mg. q 12 hours, depending on the history of light, moderate, or 
heavy heroin use over the week prior to admission). Why shouldn't the user of heroin or 
methamphetamine expect the same comfort that we give to the withdrawing alcoholic? (Besides, 
the patient will treat you better if (s)he's not suffering the illness of drug withdrawal as well as 
the other medical illness for which (s)he was admitted.) 
<p> 
Don't take it personally if the patient doesn't exactly share your priorities regarding the treatment 
of the illness versus the continuation of drug use. They may believe in a different "health belief 
model." For example, it is difficult to prevent stimulant withdrawal in the hospital. Faced with a 
choice between stimulant withdrawal or leaving AMA and taking a greater chance on failure of 
therapy, the DU may choose the latter. His/her priorities are different from yours. That doesn't 
necessarily make you right and her/him wrong. If they choose AMA, educate them on the signs 
of failure of treatment, and arrange for close follow-up. If, as usually happens if you have 
designed an effective outpatient treatment regimen, the patient gets better, (s)he has saved "the 
system" money by being treated as an outpatient, and (s)he has accepted the responsibility for 
this choice, alleviating your anxiety, guilt, over not being able to convince him/her to stay in the 
hospital for <b>your</b> treatment. 
<p> 
Treat the DU with the same respect you treat anyone else with serious, painful illness. I think 
you will find that the results of your experiment will be gratifying. Most of the time you will 
find that the patient is more cooperative. 
<p> 
Please, let me know the results of your experiment when you see me in the hall. I'd like to know 
if others experience the same success I have had, in reducing friction between patient and 
physician, improving compliance with the medical regimen, and improving the outcome of 
treatment of the illness. Also, whether changing your frame of reference has led to any 
conclusions about the "drug problem" and the "drug war" in America. 
<p> 
Neil Flynn, M.D., M.P.H.<br> 
University of California, Davis<br> 
Email: <a href="mailto:fzflynn2@peseta.ucdavis.edu">fzflynn2@peseta.ucdavis.edu</a> 
<p>
<hr> 
<p> 
<center>
<a href="http://www.lindesmith.org/tlcintro.html"><img src=subbar.jpg alt="subject index"></a><a href="http://www.lindesmith.org/tlcmain.html"><img src=hombar.jpg alt="tlc home"></a><a href="http://www.lindesmith.org/tlchot.html"><img src=hotbar.jpg alt="what's hot!"</a><br><a href="http://www.soros.org/Architext/AT-The_Lindesmith_Centerquery.html"><img src=seabar.jpg alt="search tlc"></a><a href="http://www.lindesmith.org/focal.html"><img src=focbar.jpg alt="focal point"></a><a href="http://www.lindesmith.org/tlcartic.html"><img src=libbar.jpg alt="tlc library"></a></center><p> 
</body> 
</html> 

